==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Epilogue
<hw>Ep"i*logue</hw> <pr>(?; 115)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧pilogue</ets>, L. <ets>epilogus</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/
conclusion, fr. <?/ to say in addition; <grk>'epi`</grk> upon, besides +
<?/ to say. See <er>Legend</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Drama)</fld>
<def>A speech or short poem addressed to the spectators and recited by
one of the actors, after the conclusion of the play.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A good play no <qex>epilogue</qex>, yet . . . good plays prove the
better by the help of good <qex>epilogues</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rhet.)</fld> <def>The closing part of a discourse,
in which the principal matters are recapitulated; a
conclusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>epiloguize</ent>⟦br⟧
